}

\section{\texorpdfstring{Impact on the
Standard\hyperref[impact-on-the-standard]{}}{Impact on the Standard}}\label{impact-on-the-standard}

This is a pure language extension. It:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  changes no existing valid program's meaning (code that does not
  combine \VERB|\KeywordTok{auto}| with \VERB|\KeywordTok{override}| is
  unaffected);
\item
  makes well-formed a category of declarations that are ill-formed today
  (\VERB|\KeywordTok{auto}\NormalTok{ f}\OperatorTok{()} \KeywordTok{override}|
  with no trailing-return-type on a virtual function);
\item
  requires no library changes;
\item
  requires no changes to the ABI or object model --- an
  \VERB|\KeywordTok{auto}\NormalTok{ … }\KeywordTok{override}| function
  has the same type, mangling, and vtable slot it would have had if its
  return type were written out by hand.
\end{itemize}

There are no breaking changes and no deprecations.

\section{\texorpdfstring{Implementation
experience\hyperref[implementation-experience]{}}{Implementation experience}}\label{implementation-experience}

The feature requires no novel analysis. A conforming compiler already:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  resolves which base function(s) a member overrides (to validate
  \VERB|\KeywordTok{override}| and covariance), and
\item
  has the overridden function's return type available at that point.
\end{enumerate}

Implementing the proposal amounts to: when a virtual function's declared
return type is the bare \VERB|\KeywordTok{auto}| placeholder and
\VERB|\KeywordTok{override}| is present, set the function's return type
to the overridden function's return type (after the existing override
resolution) instead of entering body-based deduction.

This has been confirmed by a prototype in Clang (against LLVM trunk).
The implementation is a \textbf{156-line additive change to Sema}, gated
behind
\VERB|\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{std}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{c}\OperatorTok{++}\DecValTok{2}\ErrorTok{c}|,
and reuses machinery the compiler already runs --- override resolution
(which executes while the member is declared) and the existing
\VERB|\KeywordTok{auto}| return-type deduction. Concretely:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  the existing ``different return type'' diagnostic is \emph{deferred}
  when an overriding function's declared return type is the bare
  \VERB|\KeywordTok{auto}| placeholder;
\item
  once the \VERB|\KeywordTok{override}| specifier and the set of
  overridden functions are known, the function's return type is set to
  the overridden type and fixed at the declaration, so vtable layout and
  override checking proceed exactly as for a written-out type;
\item
  each \VERB|\ControlFlowTok{return}| statement is checked against that
  type with no implicit conversion;
\item
  mixing \VERB|\KeywordTok{auto}| and the written-out type across an
  in-class declaration and an out-of-line definition is reconciled in
  the existing redeclaration-merging step, with a disagreeing
  written-out type diagnosed; and
\item
  a feature-test macro
  \VERB|\NormalTok{\_\_cpp\_deduced\_virtual\_override\_return}| is
  defined.
\end{itemize}

The prototype passes a positive/negative conformance suite covering
every case in this paper --- the basic form, all four
\VERB|\KeywordTok{auto}|/written-out out-of-line combinations, a
dependent return type, cv- and \VERB|\KeywordTok{noexcept}|-qualified
overrides, and each ill-formed case (return-operand mismatch, missing
\VERB|\KeywordTok{override}|,
\VERB|\KeywordTok{decltype}\OperatorTok{(}\KeywordTok{auto}\OperatorTok{)}|,
disagreeing multiple bases, and a disagreeing out-of-line definition)
--- together with an in-tree \VERB|\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{verify}|
test. Existing override, covariance, and ordinary
\VERB|\KeywordTok{auto}|-deduction behaviour is unchanged, and the same
spelling remains ill-formed before C++26. The branch is available at
\emph{github.com/Alex-Tsvetanov/llvm-project} (branch
\VERB|\KeywordTok{auto}\OperatorTok{{-}}\ControlFlowTok{return}\OperatorTok{{-}}\KeywordTok{override}|).

\section{\texorpdfstring{Future
directions\hyperref[future]{}}{Future directions}}\label{future}

The following are intentionally \textbf{out of scope} for this paper but
are natural follow-ups:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{\VERB|\KeywordTok{decltype}\OperatorTok{(}\KeywordTok{auto}\OperatorTok{)}|
  overrides.} Could be defined to copy the base type with its value
  category, though the practical benefit over \VERB|\KeywordTok{auto}|
  is small.
\item
  \textbf{Deduced covariant return types.} Allowing
  \VERB|\KeywordTok{auto}| to deduce a covariant type from the body
  (rather than copying the base type exactly) was considered and
  rejected for R0 in favor of a simpler rule; it could be revisited.
\item
  \textbf{Dropping the \VERB|\KeywordTok{override}| requirement.}
  Permitting deduction for any overriding function was rejected (see
  {[}design.trigger{]}); revisiting it would require a story for silent
  overrides and accidental coupling.
\end{itemize}

